# PRD: Crash Details Full-Page Experience

## 1. Product Summary
The crash reporting experience should allow a user to select a crash from the crash list and view its complete details in a dedicated full-page experience. The selected crash details should be presented in a structured layout that includes exception information, application context, device context, and thread-level diagnostics.

## 2. Problem Statement
Users need to investigate crash incidents in detail, including the underlying exception, environment context, and thread stack traces. A full-page details view will provide a clearer and more focused experience than an inline or overlay-based interaction.

## 3. Goals
- Provide a dedicated crash details page for each selected crash.
- Present all relevant crash data in a clear, structured, and readable format.
- Support navigation back to the crash list.
- Support navigation between crash occurrences for the same crash group.
- Make thread diagnostics easier to inspect through expandable sections.

## 4. User Stories
- As a product analyst, I want to open a crash from the crash list so that I can inspect its complete details.
- As a support engineer, I want to view app and device context so that I can understand the environment of the crash.
- As a developer, I want to inspect thread stack traces so that I can identify the root cause.
- As a user, I want to return to the crash list easily so that I can continue investigating other issues.

## 5. Functional Requirements
### 5.1 Crash Selection
- Selecting a crash from the crash list opens a dedicated details page.
- The page should replace the main crash list view while the details are being displayed.
- The user should be able to return to the crash list through a clearly labeled action.

### 5.2 Crash Header
The details page must display:
- Crash title
- Crash severity
- Crash occurrence count and current occurrence position
- Back button
- Previous/Next occurrence navigation

### 5.3 Crash Summary
The details page must show:
- Exception name
- Exception code
- Session ID
- Crash title
- Stack summary

### 5.4 Application Context
The details page must display:
- App orientation
- Current view/screen name

### 5.5 Device Context
The details page must display:
- Device model
- Device machine
- CPU
- OS build version
- OS display version
- Total memory
- Memory used
- Total storage
- Storage used

### 5.6 Thread Details
The details page must display all available threads for the crash.
Each thread must show:
- Thread name
- Thread ID
- Whether it is the main thread
- Whether it crashed
- Status label: Active or Crashed

Each thread must be expandable/collapsible.
By default, all thread sections should be collapsed.
When expanded, each thread must display:
- Stack summary
- Stack frames table

### 5.7 Stack Frames
Each thread’s stack frames table must include:
- Frame index
- Module/library
- Function/symbol
- Address
- Offset
- Crash indicator

The crashed frame should be visually highlighted.

## 6. Data Requirements
The data team must provide the following fields for each crash detail:
- exceptionName
- exceptionCodeName
- title
- sessionId
- application.orientation
- application.currentView
- device.model
- device.machine
- device.cpu
- device.osBuildVersion
- device.osDisplayVersion
- device.memoryTotal
- device.memoryUsed
- device.storageTotal
- device.storageUsed
- thread.id
- thread.name
- thread.crashed
- thread.main
- threads[]
- stackSummary
- stackFrames[] with index, library, symbol, address, offset, crashed

## 7. UI/UX Requirements
- The details experience should feel like a dedicated page, not an overlay.
- The layout should be structured and easy to scan.
- The interface should use the existing product styling and color palette.
- Crash-relevant states should use the existing red accent styling.
- Expand/collapse controls should be clear and intuitive.

## 8. Accessibility Requirements
- All navigation controls must be keyboard accessible.
- Focus states must be visible.
- Expand/collapse controls must be operable without a mouse.
- Color contrast must meet accessibility standards.

## 9. Acceptance Criteria
- Clicking a crash from the list opens a dedicated details page.
- The page contains exception, application, device, and thread information.
- The user can return to the crash list.
- The user can navigate between crash occurrences.
- Threads are collapsible and collapsed by default.
- All required data is rendered correctly from the provided payload.
